`SimpleDateFormat` can not handle fraction-of-second up to microseconds resolution, its limit is up to millisecond resolution. If you try to parse it as it is, you will get the wrong result as explained in [this answer](https://stackoverflow.com/a/74932671/10819573).

You have two choices:
1. Truncate fraction of second up to milliseconds resolution.
2. Use ThreeTenABP or [Android desugaring support](https://developer.android.com/studio/write/java8-support-table) as explained in [this post](https://stackoverflow.com/q/38922754/10819573). You can then use [`Instant#parse`](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/time/Instant.html#parse-java.lang.CharSequence-) to parse your date-time string into an `Instant`. 

**Note:** You need to use `X` instead of `Z` in your pattern.

**Demo**:

    import java.text.ParseException;
    import java.text.SimpleDateFormat;
    
